    <title>The Plucky Squire is an adorable adventure that mixes 2D and 3D</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="A screenshot from the video game The Plucky Squire." src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/RgjFwk4BMNkpC-pzAY4-rNbYXxk=/150x0:1770x1080/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73600704/ss_2c4b9f2614e2b4344ee7734649fe126550fe5c65.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;Image: All Possible Futures&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="lfhK5o"&gt;&lt;em&gt;The Plucky Squire&lt;/em&gt; is a game that leaps off the page — literally. It takes place in a storybook world rendered in an adorable two dimensions thanks to codirector and former &lt;em&gt;Pokémon&lt;/em&gt; artist &lt;a href="https://www.instagram.com/jamesturner_42/"&gt;James Turner&lt;/a&gt;. But at certain points, the heroic lead character can venture into the real world and solve puzzles that mix 2D and 3D in inventive ways. Sometimes, you’re moving objects between dimensions; other times, you’re rearranging the words in a book to create new outcomes. It’s as cute as it is creative, and it follows &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/24237778/astro-bot-review-ps5-game-of-the-year"&gt;Sony’s &lt;em&gt;Astro Bot&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt; in what is turning out to be a very good year for family-friendly games.&lt;/p&gt;
