    <title>Cards Against Humanity is suing SpaceX for trespassing on its ‘pristine’ property</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="Photo collage of Elon Musk." src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/dUE5f6RLr4QsS2-wxDCsnRRw28M=/20x0:2021x1334/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73599753/STK022_ELON_MUSK_CVIRGINIA_C.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;Image: Cath Virginia / The Verge | Photo by STR / NurPhoto, Getty Images&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="K2zd6X"&gt;Cards Against Humanity sued SpaceX for allegedly trespassing on and damaging its property in Texas. The company behind the card game is asking for $15 million in damages, according to its &lt;a href="https://www.documentcloud.org/documents/25169455-cards-against-humanity-v-spacex-elon-musk?responsive=1&amp;amp;title=1"&gt;complaint&lt;/a&gt; against SpaceX, filed in Texas state court on Thursday, but &lt;a href="https://www.cahsuesmusk.com/"&gt;has also said&lt;/a&gt; it will “accept Twitter.com in compensation.” &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="caNP7l"&gt;SpaceX has been using the “pristine vacant property” in Cameron County, Texas, without permission for around six months, the suit claims. Cards Against Humanity bought the plot in 2017 as part of a stunt to “make it as time-consuming and expensive as possible for [former President Donald] Trump to build his wall.” SpaceX has since acquired “many of the vacant lots” on the road surrounding Cards Against Humanity’s property,...&lt;/p&gt;
